snippet.textDisplay:
I would agree Kylo/Ben’s arch was the best thing to watch in the sequel trilogy. Any time he was on screen, I was engaged—no doubt because of Driver’s talent for emotional intensity and commitment. I liked everything regarding that character in this film save for the fact that he didn’t really help Rey with Palpatine aside from encouraging her with his presence and trading his life to restore hers at the end.

I’m sure Disney was commited to the “strong girl stands alone” trope, but as a female viewer, I’m not offended at the idea of strong women working alongside someone else and getting (gasp) help.

I liked the kiss—it was sweet and my husband high fived me to the sound of cheerful teenagers in the audience as it happened. The smile was precious. The death was bittersweet but an understandable end to the character. I do like the idea of Ben surviving, because Star Wars has explored the evil character redeeming themselves through self sacrifice before. It’d be interesting to explore a now good character living in light of their past evil—how does someone live with that? What do they do with a life they know they don’t deserve, but have been graciously given? But some folks would hate it. I like redemption stories—unmerited grace, forgiveness, restoring bad things into better things rather than destruction, mercy—all good stuff I think our culture should keep bringing up in our stories. Especially fairy tales like Star Wars.

Also force babies would’ve been cool. Judge me, I don’t care. 😂

That's the problem, JJ and Disney were trying to please everyone, and I'm a fan, I inherently want to be pleased. But not at the sake of a poor story. There are things as a fan I don't like in the other movies, but those choices made sense in the grand scheme of the story. It felt like, true Force Awakens and TLJ had conflicting ideas, but rather than trying to retconn those ideas to return to his ideas, JJ could have attempted to cohesively join their conflicting ideas even if it came at the cost of his own.
The thing is, unlike it seems a lot of people, I love every single Star Wars movie and have on multiple occasions rewatched them all multiple times, both individually and as a series. Until this one. This is the one Star Wars movie I don't think I'll be wanting to rewatch. The choices made, like reviving Palpatine, just seem to invalidate Anakin's redemption, etc. This movie makes all the others harder to watch knowing how the Skywalker saga truly ends.

snippet.textDisplay: Say whatever you want about the Prequels, and maybe even the Originals, but Lucas had a vision, a road map and even a message through their story. For the Sequels, after watching Rogue One and Star Wars Rebels about 3 years ago, I had a lot of hope for the story of the Sequel Trilogy, because even if I liked The Force Awakens, I had a bit of difficulties with the story which has already begun. But after watching The Last Jedi, it really felt that there was no road map for the story of the ST and I was also about to say a farewell to Star Wars as a whole. So I came to watch The Rise of Skywalker yesterday with very low expectations. After I came out of the theater I told myself that it was satisfying but the story felt a bit all over the place and the entire story of the ST didn't mean more for me.

snippet.textDisplay:
My opinion on this movie is honestly almost the opposite of yours. I didn't like The Force Awakens (it felt too much like a clone of A New Hope), and I didn't like The Last Jedi (too much random garbage that didn't make sense). But honestly, I really liked The Rise of Skywalker, to the point that it started to make me like the other two movies better. Here's how I think about it. After my disappointment with The Last Jedi, I started thinking about how I would have written this sequel trilogy. And one of the big things that caught my eye in this movie was Palpatine. That was one of the main plot points as I'd written it - that Palpatine would return as a clone in another body (it's from an expanded universe thing). And the reason why I think that works is this. The ending of Return of the Jedi is nice, but it isn't very logical. The war hasn't ended, the Empire isn't dead, and Anakin hasn't brought balance to the Force. The movie wants us to think those things are true, but they aren't. More importantly, the main things tying the two trilogies together were Anakin and Palpatine. Really, those movies were their story. And Anakin died at the end of The Last Jedi. He could - and should - have shown up as a Force ghost or something like that, but he could never play a huge role in the new trilogy. And that means that we need Palpatine to return as the main antagonist. If he wasn't in the new trilogy, it would have felt disconnected from the original two. Snoke and Kylo Ren - however much they may have evolved - started life as bargain-basket Palpatine and Vader. They needed more than that. They needed the original characters to come back and fill those roles, and they needed their own story.
As far as the movie itself goes, I loved it. It was not perfect - too much of the Disney brand of comedy, which sickens my to my cynical core - but it was really good. It had almost the same runtime as The Last Jedi, but where The Last Jedi felt long and pointless, The Rise of Skywalker made good use of its runtime. Not a minute was wasted. And honestly, I liked the story and the dozen character arcs. It felt balanced and fast-paced at the same time, and I liked that. More importantly, though, it captured the feeling that the original Star Wars had - that feeling of a movie that looked like sci-fi, but felt like fantasy. That sense was very strong in The Rise of Skywalker. Whereas The Last Jedi felt more like it was trying to be hard science fiction, but not doing very well because it's Star Wars, The Rise of Skywalker felt almost like high fantasy, but in space. It embraced that sense. I dunno, maybe I'm rambling. But I really liked it.
